│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe transformation sequence rewrites a              │
│ floating-point select guarded-by-compare into a maxnum followed by an fadd.   │
│ Alive2 shows the new IR is more poisonous than the original when %in = -inf.  │
│ The original select avoids propagating the poison from the unchosen fadd      │
│ operand, but after converting the select to a maxnum intrinsic with 'ninf'    │
│ fast-math flag, the call becomes poison in the presence of an infinite        │
│ operand, even though the result would be finite. This violates                │
│ refinement.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\n- First, foldSelectIntoAddConstant    │
│ rewrites: select (fcmp ...) (fadd X, C) C => fadd(select X/0, C). It also     │
│ propagates FMF to both the new select and fadd.\n- Next, visitSelectInst      │
│ recognizes the select-with-fcmp and converts it to maxnum due to nnan and     │
│ nsz: \"Canonicalize select of FP values where NaN and -0.0 are not valid as   │
│ minnum/maxnum intrinsics.\" The resulting call carries nnan ninf nsz. The log │
│ shows: %sel = call nnan ninf nsz @llvm.maxnum.f32(...)\n- Alive2 demonstrates │
│ a counterexample: %in = -inf makes the source select return 1.0 (no poison),  │
│ while the target has poison at the maxnum call because 'ninf' is set.\n\n3.   │
│ Root Cause Analysis:\nThe conversion from select to maxnum/minnum incorrectly │
│ carries 'no-infs' (and other builder FMF) onto the intrinsic. 'ninf' on       │
│ select is effectively inert (select doesn't interpret FMF), but 'ninf' on     │
│ maxnum changes semantics: it forbids infinite operands/results and is modeled │
│ as poison when violated. Thus, when %in = -inf, the intrinsic becomes poison, │
│ whereas the original select was safe since the poisoned value (%add) was      │
│ unselected.\n\nConcretely, in InstCombineSelect.cpp around lines 3929–3943,   │
│ we create the intrinsic via IRBuilder. Because Builder may have FMF taken     │
│ from the select, the newly created intrinsic inherits 'ninf' and 'nsz'. The   │
│ code only setsHasNoNaNs, which does not clear preexisting flags, so 'ninf'    │
│ remains. We must explicitly clear FMF on the intrinsic and then set only the  │
│ intended subset (nnan). This matches the intent of the comment and avoids     │
│ strengthening semantics.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\n- File:                │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineSelect.cpp\n  - Edit region        │
│ 3931–3934 (maxnum path):\n    Replace the current post-creation FMF           │
│ handling:\n      if (auto *BinIntrInst = dyn_cast<Instruction>(BinIntr))\n    │
│ BinIntrInst->setHasNoNaNs(FCmp->hasNoNaNs());\n    with logic that clears FMF │
│ and sets only nnan as appropriate:\n      if (auto *BinIntrInst =             │
│ dyn_cast<Instruction>(BinIntr)) {\n        FastMathFlags FMF; // empty =>     │
│ clears all flags\n        if (FCmp && FCmp->hasNoNaNs())\n                    │
│ FMF.setNoNaNs(true);\n        BinIntrInst->setFastMathFlags(FMF);\n           │
│ }\n\n  - Edit region 3938–3943 (minnum path):\n    Similarly, replace the     │
│ setHasNoNaNs call with the same FMF reset-and-set pattern as above for the    │
│ minnum intrinsic.\n\nRationale: These changes ensure the maxnum/minnum calls  │
│ do not retain 'ninf' (or any other unintended FMF like 'nsz') from the        │
│ Builder or the original select. We only attach 'nnan' when justified by the   │
│ compare, matching the existing intent in the code and avoiding                │
│ over-constraining the intrinsic.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe bug stems from        │
│ unintended FMF propagation when converting a select to maxnum/minnum.         │
│ Clearing the FMF on the created intrinsic and then setting only NoNaNs (if    │
│ warranted) prevents the introduction of 'ninf', thereby eliminating the extra │
│ poison observed by Alive2. This preserves correctness while keeping the       │
│ intended optimization."})                                                     │
