│ ```                                                                           │
│                                                                               │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The transformation sequence rewrites a floating-point select                  │
│ guarded-by-compare into a maxnum followed by an fadd. Alive2 shows the new IR │
│ is more poisonous than the original when %in = -inf. The original select      │
│ avoids propagating the poison from the unchosen fadd operand, but after       │
│ converting the select to a maxnum intrinsic with 'ninf' fast-math flag, the   │
│ call becomes poison in the presence of an infinite operand, even though the   │
│ result would be finite. This violates refinement.                             │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ - First, foldSelectIntoAddConstant rewrites: select (fcmp ...) (fadd X, C) C  │
│ => fadd(select X/0, C). It also propagates FMF to both the new select and     │
│ fadd.                                                                         │
│ - Next, visitSelectInst recognizes the select-with-fcmp and converts it to    │
│ maxnum due to nnan and nsz: "Canonicalize select of FP values where NaN and   │
│ -0.0 are not valid as minnum/maxnum intrinsics." The resulting call carries   │
│ nnan ninf nsz. The log shows: %sel = call nnan ninf nsz @llvm.maxnum.f32(...) │
│ - Alive2 demonstrates a counterexample: %in = -inf makes the source select    │
│ return 1.0 (no poison), while the target has poison at the maxnum call        │
│ because 'ninf' is set.                                                        │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ The conversion from select to maxnum/minnum incorrectly carries 'no-infs'     │
│ (and other builder FMF) onto the intrinsic. 'ninf' on select is effectively   │
│ inert (select doesn't interpret FMF), but 'ninf' on maxnum changes semantics: │
│ it forbids infinite operands/results and is modeled as poison when violated.  │
│ Thus, when %in = -inf, the intrinsic becomes poison, whereas the original     │
│ select was safe since the poisoned value (%add) was unselected.               │
│                                                                               │
│ Concretely, in InstCombineSelect.cpp around lines 3929–3943, we create the    │
│ intrinsic via IRBuilder. Because Builder may have FMF taken from the select,  │
│ the newly created intrinsic inherits 'ninf' and 'nsz'. The code only          │
│ setsHasNoNaNs, which does not clear preexisting flags, so 'ninf' remains. We  │
│ must explicitly clear FMF on the intrinsic and then set only the intended     │
│ subset (nnan). This matches the intent of the comment and avoids              │
│ strengthening semantics.                                                      │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)                                                     │
│ - File: llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineSelect.cpp                 │
│   - Edit region 3931–3934 (maxnum path):                                      │
│     Replace the current post-creation FMF handling:                           │
│       if (auto *BinIntrInst = dyn_cast<Instruction>(BinIntr))                 │
│         BinIntrInst->setHasNoNaNs(FCmp->hasNoNaNs());                         │
│     with logic that clears FMF and sets only nnan as appropriate:             │
│       if (auto *BinIntrInst = dyn_cast<Instruction>(BinIntr)) {               │
│         FastMathFlags FMF; // empty => clears all flags                       │
│         if (FCmp && FCmp->hasNoNaNs())                                        │
│           FMF.setNoNaNs(true);                                                │
│         BinIntrInst->setFastMathFlags(FMF);                                   │
│       }                                                                       │
│                                                                               │
│   - Edit region 3938–3943 (minnum path):                                      │
│     Similarly, replace the setHasNoNaNs call with the same FMF reset-and-set  │
│ pattern as above for the minnum intrinsic.                                    │
│                                                                               │
│ Rationale: These changes ensure the maxnum/minnum calls do not retain 'ninf'  │
│ (or any other unintended FMF like 'nsz') from the Builder or the original     │
│ select. We only attach 'nnan' when justified by the compare, matching the     │
│ existing intent in the code and avoiding over-constraining the intrinsic.     │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ The bug stems from unintended FMF propagation when converting a select to     │
│ maxnum/minnum. Clearing the FMF on the created intrinsic and then setting     │
│ only NoNaNs (if warranted) prevents the introduction of 'ninf', thereby       │
│ eliminating the extra poison observed by Alive2. This preserves correctness   │
│ while keeping the intended optimization.                                      │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
